                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>The Product Rule and Integration</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Recall, the product rule tells us
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx}(f(x) \cdot g(x)) = f'(x) g(x) + f(x) g'(x)
                            </me>,
                            or equivalently, 
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            <me>
                                \displaystyle \int f'(x)g(x) + f(x)g'(x) \quad dx = f(x) \cdot g(x) + C
                            </me>.

                            We can rearrange this as shown in class to obtain the formula for <term>integration by parts</term>:
                            <me>
                                \displaystyle \int f(x)g'(x) \quad dx = f(x)g(x) - \int f'(x)g(x) \quad dx
                            </me>.
                            The shorthand version using differentials is
                            <me>
                                \displaystyle \int u \quad dv = uv - \int v \quad du
                            </me>.
                            
                            
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>A First Example</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int xe^x \quad dx</m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            If we choose <m>u=x</m> and <m>dv = e^x \quad dx</m>, then we can solve for <m>du = dx</m> and
                            <m>v = e^x</m> to get 
                            <me>
                                \int xe^x \quad dx = xe^x - \int e^x \quad dx = xe^x - e^x +C
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Integration By Parts</title>
                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int x\cos(x) \quad dx</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Choose <m>u=x</m> and <m>dv = \cos(x) \quad dx</m>. Using IBP and solving we should get
                                <me>
                                    \int x\cos(x) \quad dx = x\sin(x) + \cos(x) + C
                                </me>.
                                
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int \ln(x) \quad dx</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Choose <m>u=\ln(x)</m> and <m>dv =  dx</m>. Using IBP and solving we should get
                                <me>
                                    \int \ln(x) \quad dx = x\ln(x) -x + C
                                </me>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                        
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int x^2 e^x\quad dx</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Choose <m>u=x^2</m> and <m>dv = e^x \quad dx</m>. Using IBP (twice, the second 
                                using <m>u=2x</m> and <m>dv = e^x \quad dx</m>) and solving we should get
                                <me>
                                    \int x^2 e^x\quad dx = x^2e^x - 2xe^x + 2e^x +C
                                </me>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="3in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int e^x\cos(x) \quad dx</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Choose <m>u=\cos(x)</m> and <m>dv = e^x \quad dx</m>. Using IBP (twice, the second 
                                using <m>u=\sin(x)</m> and <m>dv = e^x \quad dx</m>) and using the
                                "boomerang" trick, we should get
                                <me>
                                    \int e^x\cos(x)\quad dx = \frac{e^x\cos(x) + e^x\sin(x)}{2} +C
                                </me>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

